{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_goblin_ver01/data/sn82015425/00529040982/1958040901/0585.xml":{"full_text":"A New \"Veep\" Sought\nTeachers\nNominate\n4 Tonight\nCOLUMBUS. Four candidates\nwill be nominated for the vice\npresident of the Georgia Teachers\nand Education Association tonight\nat the opening session of the 40th\nannual State Convention here\nat Spencer Senior High School.\nTn the race for the post to be\nvacated Charles L. Butler, Augusta,\nwho succeeds H. E. Tate, former\nprincipal of Fairmont High School,\nGriffin are Robert A. Bryant, Cedar\nHills High School, Cedartown;\nRobert Threatt, classroom teacher,\nSpencer Junior High School, Col\numbus.. Daniel T. Grant, Wash\nington Consolidates School, Cairo;\nand John w. Lofton, principal, WiL\nlow Hili Hi^h School, Statesboro\nPOLITICKING\nOld-fashioned politicking will\nmark the nomination campaign\nanu set off what observers believe\nwill be on e of the most interesting\nelections in years. This was viewed\nbecause of the large number of\ncandidates for the post.\nThe winner in th e vice-presiden\ntial race will automatically succeed\npresident-elect Butler two years\nfrom now. Mr. Butler was elected\nin 1956 when the state convention\nheld its annual meeting in Augusta.\nL. H Pitts, executive secretary,\nannounced Tuesday that following\ntonight's nomination speeches the\nGTEA will hear various reports\nwhich will be submitted to the\nentire convention Thursday morn\ning at the City Auditorium.\nassociation meets\nThe Georgia Interscholastic As\nsociation meets here this morning\nat eleven am.\nC. W- DuVaul, principal of Spen\ncer Senior High School, is host to\nthe statewide meeting along with\nthe Muscogee Teachers Association.\nNew directors from several regions\nwill be formally installed following\n\u25a0the nominations tonight.\nNEW DIRECTORS\nAmong the new directors to serve\nuntil the 1960 session are Region\n2, W. A. Bush, Henderson High\nSchool, Jackson; Region 3, A. J.\nMartin, principal. Herring High\nSchool, Decatur; Region 3, Pharris\nT. Johnson, Athens High School,\nAthens; Region 4, John W. Lofton,\nWillow Hili High School, States\nboro; Region 5, Robert Blount, Levi\nWhite Elementary School, Augusta;\nRegion 7, H. E. Bryant, principal,\nHunt High School, Fort Valley;\nRegion 8, James Brown, Unvalda\nElementary School, Unvalda; Reg\nion 9, C. E. Stanley, Washington\nHigh School, Blakley; Region 10,\nJ. J. Cantrell, J. W. Hmlis School,\nSylvester.\nHates \"Peeking\" Folks,\nAged Man Sprays House\nAnd Street With Shots\nNASHVILLE, Tenn. (INS) A\n70-year-old Nashville man went\nberserk Monday because he eaid he\ndidn't like people \u201cpeeking\u201d through\nhis window.\nFred Nickens blasted holes in\n(the window of his home and spray\ned a busy Nashville Street with\nshot gun pellets before police\nquieted him.\nNobody was hurt, but Nickens\nvowed as he was led away, \u201cI\u2019m\ngoing to blast them every time\niltey look into my window.\u201d\nSUIT SEEKS PASSPORT\nFOR NEGRO REPORTER\nWASHINGTON, D. C. (NNPA) The American Civil\nLiberties Union Tuesday filed in the District Court here a suit\non behalf of William Worthy, of Boston, an Afro-American cor\nrespondent, to compel the Secretary to issue his passport.\nChallenging the righit of the State\nDepartment to deny him a. pass\nport, Mr. Worthy asks the court to\ndeclare invalid the regulations is\nsued by the Secretary of State gov\nerning the issuance of passports.\nMr. Worthy asserts that these\nregulations violate his constitution\nal right to travel, imposed foreign\npolicy conditions upon the right to\ntravel in violation also of the Con\nstitution, establish unconstitution\nally vague conditions, constitute\nan unlawful assumption, by the\nSecretary of State of legislative\npower, and fail to give him the\nkind of hearing to which he is en\ntitled under the Constitution\nAs a representative of the press,\nMr. Worthy insists, he is entitled\nto a passport under the First\nAmendment to the Constitution.\nHe asks the court to issue a decree\nto that effect. The First Amend\nment guarantees freedom of the\npress.\nMr. Worthy also asks the court\nto enjoin Secretary of State John\nFoster Duties from denying him a\nrenewal of his passport and to di\nrect Mr. Dulles to renew his pass\nport upon tiie same terms as are\napplicable to American citizens\ngenerally\nThe complaint, filed through\nWilliam M. Kunstler, an attorney\nof New York City, states that Mr.\nWorthy was refused his passport\nt JCcotiMtd M <1\nVOLUME 30, NUMBER 211\n-dt HL\n-r/WDT d\nV awe ZZ\nrti\nisg&iS JHT l\n-\u2019XL RR*\nWIN WOODROW WILSON AWARDS Miss Carrie Fair of Ashe\nville and Julius L. Chambers of Mt. Gilead, seniors at North\nCarolina College, are recipients of Woodrow Wilson Fellowships\nin the amount of $2,700 each for graduate study next school\nyear. Miss Fair is a political science major and a senior coun\nselor at NCC. Chambers, history major, is president of the NCC\nStudent Government Association.\nTheologian Declares\nCHURCH SEGREGATION'S\nMAIN INSTRUMENT NOW\nNEW YORK The Church of Jesus Christ has become the\nprimary instrument for the perpetuation of segregated life, ac\ncording to an article in the new issue of Esquire Magazine.\nNigerians Called\nAstute Investors\nBy United States\nWASHINGTON. (ANP) The\nXL MR \u00a9apartment of Commerce\nstated this week in a special report\nthat an increasing number of Niger\nians who have built up savings\nfrom trade or farming activities\n\u201care more ana more directing their\ninvestments into other than the\nfamiliar channels.\u201d\nFor example, it was noted, Niger\nian-African financed companies are\ncurrently active in importing and\nexporting and have gone into varied\nenterprises as manufacture of cere\nmics and undershirts (singlots),\ntire retreading, commercial road\ntransport, and river shipping.\nSTANDARDS CHANGED\nThe Commerce Department ex\nperts frankly admitted that Niger\nian \u201cexpatriate\u201d companies such as\nBritish-owned concerns \u201chave not\nalways given their support to the\nspread of Nigerian enterprises:\nhowever, in recent years, they have\nchanged noticeably.\u201d\nThe revelation was made that\nmany Nigerians are replacing fore,\nIgn personnel as experience is ac\nquired.\n'\u2022\u2019Although it is difficult,\u201d the re\nport continued, \u201cto amass statistics\non the subject, it is believed that a\nsizeable number of Africans with\nlnvestabl e funds would be willing\nand even anxious to join with\nforeign private capital in given\n(Continued on Page 4, Col. 6)\nWild West's\nPistol Pete\nDies At 97\nPERKINS, Okla. (INS)\u2014 Frank\n\u201cPistol Pete\u201d Eaton\u2014famous Indian\nterritory lawman whose six gun\ncontained 11 notches for men he\nkilled died Tuesday at his Per\nkins home at the age of 97.\nThe oldtime cowboy, Indian\nfighter and. lawman who once serv\ned as a deputy U. S. marshall un\nder \u201cHanging Judge\u201d Isaac C.\nParker of Fort Smith, Ark., had\nbeen in failing health since Feb\nruary when he broke his pelvis in\na fall.\nFuneral arrangements for Eaton\nare still pending.\nUntil his death, Pistol Pete as\nhe was most widely known, dress\ned in Western clothes, wore cow\nboy hat and boots and kept his\nhair long and braided in Indian\nstyle.\nHis pistol supposedly had 11\nnotches, five for gunning down the\noutlaw killers of his father and six\n(Gyotias^ n fan 4\u00bb Col. >1\nAtlanta World\nPublished Every Morning Except Monday\nTel.: JAckson 1-1459\nThe author of thia article, Dr.\nWesley Shrader, a Baptist minister,\ncalls the situation \u201cthe most strik\ning irony of the twentieth century\u201d\nand predicts that the church will\nbe \u201cthe last bastion to fall\u2014if, in\ndeed, it will ever fall.\u201d\nDr. Shrader, born and educated\nin the South and now an associate\nprofessor of Pastoral Theology at\nYale University\u2019s Divinity School,\nsays the deplorable situation Is not\nconfined to the South. \u201cBut it is\nmore dramatically seen in the\nSouth,\u201d he explains, \u201cwhere the\nChristian church openly rMXWhts\nthe greatest bulwark of Segregated\npower.\u201d\nLARGEST DENOMINATION\nThe largest religious denomina\ntion in the South is the Southern\nBaptist Convention claiming 30,000\nchurches and 8,500,000 members,\nsays the theologian. This group has\nrevised its age-long method of re\nceiving new members to order to\ninsure its congregations will re\nmain all white.\nDr. Shrader says that one large\nchurch in South Carolina has de\nleted the following kindly phrase\nfrom its church bulletin: To all\nwho are weary and need rest; to\nall who are lonely and need friend\nship; to all who sin and need a\nSaviour, this church opens wide its\ndoors and in the name of Jesus\nChrist you come.\nULTIMATE STEP\nA Baptist church in Rocky\nMount, N. C\u201e says Esquire, has\ntaken the ultimate step by declar\ning itself to be a segregated church\nnow and forever. A section of Its\nconstitution has-been rewritten to\nread: \u201cThe membership of this\n(Continued on Page 4, CoL 3)\nAtlanta Station\nTo Show Tribute\nTo Handy Tonight\nNEW YORK (ANP)\u2014A musical\ntribute to the late W. C. Handy\nwill highlight an hour-long NBC\nTV spectacular, \u201cSwing Into\nSpring,\u201d sponsored by the Texas\nOil Company, Wednesday.\nIn Atlanta it will be heard over\nWSB-TV at 9 o\u2019clock tonight.\nRunning from 9 to 10 pm., the\nspisctacular will present \u201cSt. Louis\nBlues\u201d and other jazz classics com\nposed by the great Handy, with\nrenditions by Benny Goodman and\norchestra, Harry James, Ella Fitz\ngerald and! Jo Stafford. Miss Fitz\ngerald stars in Paramount\u2019s \u201cSt.\nLouis Dliuesj\u201d film biography of\nHandy, who died March 28. Nat\n\u201cKing\u201d Cole plays the role of\nHandy in the picture.\nWorld premiere of \u201cSt. Louis\nBlues\u201d will >be held Thursday, April\n10, in St. Louis as a memorial tri\nbute to Handy.\nLAFF-A-DAY\nI I\n*T don\u2019t know whether I'D run\nfor another term or not. My\n(mil \u0964hi -MC\nATLANTA (3), GEORGIA, WEDNESDAY, APRIL 9, 1958\nAfricans\nTo Get\nVote Right\nUNITED NATIONS, N. Y. (ANP)\n\u2014lnformation received here from\nNorthern Rhodesia in Central\nAfrica revealed that the govern\nment of that country presented\nthis week proposals for a \u201cgradual\ntransition\u201d to a non-racial com\nmon roll franchise.\nOfficially the proposals will be\nsubmitted to the British Colonial\nOffice in London \u201cwith any amend\nments to enable the changes to be\nintroduced in time for the elections\nnext February (1959).\nHowever, even with the proposals\nstill to be discussed, they fall far\nshort of even moderate African\nopinion\u2019s expectations.\nUnder the new proposals there\nwould be two nominated African\nmembers of the Legislative Coun\ncil out of 30 members. However,\nporvlsions will be made for other\nAfricans to be elected from six\nconstituencies predominantly Afri\ncan In composition.\nReportedly the new development\nis that a special franchise has been\nintroduced whereby the \u201cfinancial\n(Continued on Page 4, Col. 6)\nIwi Iml\n\u2019lmm\nuMH^B\nMMMaRPiI\n\u25a0l^'^ i\nNATIONAL SORORITIES TAKE SPOTLIGHT HERE\nTwo national sororities took a pre-Easter\nspotlight in Atlanta, Georgia, climaxing an\nnual Southern regional conferences with many\ninteresting programs. In upper photo regional\nofficers, Dr. Lorraine Williams, Washington, D.\nC.; Mrs. Cleo Higgins, Palatka, Florida; Mrs.\nWinfred Jones, Atlanta, Ga.; and Miss Dariens\nHutson, Jackson, Tenn., confer during a roll I\ncall vote at one of Sigma Gamma Rho sessions. I\nCreative writing students from Washington High I\nCitizens' Housing Group\nBacks Fairplay Program\nBy WILLIAM A. FOWLKES\n(World Managing Editor)\nThe position of the Over-all Citizens Committee of Slum\nClearance and Urban Renewal remains the same and it is, still\nstanding by its March statement, calling for fairplay in Atlan\nta's multi-million-dollar development, it was learned from a re\nliable source Tuesday. It was also stated that progress was\nbeing made in negotiations to iron out objectives to first drafts\nof Atlanta's proposed program.\nThe committee, headed by Bishop\nW. R. Wilkes, voted to make no\nstatement to the press, following a\nclosed meeting.\nThe meeting had been called in\nthe wake of a controversy over the\ndeveloping program, highlighted by\na verbal blast by Mayor William B.\nHartsfield against the Atlanta\nNAACP and its president, John H.\nCalhoun. The attack centered\naround a press released resolution\nfrom the Atlanta branch, adopted\nseveral weeks ago, but given to\nnewspapers and federal agencies\nlast week. The NAAGP resolution\ncalled upon \u201call agencies concerned\nwith Atlanta\u2019s slum clearance pro\ngram and urban renewal to deny\napproval until solutions to the\nproblems ar e devised and esta\nblished..\u201d\nMr. Hartsfield, unavailable for\nfurther comment Tuesday, had\nsaid th\u00ae resolution was an attempt\nto stop the urban renewal-re\ndevelopment program. Mr. Calhoun\ndenied any blanket attempt to stop\nthe slum clearance program, point\ning out that the resolution was an\nattempt to protect the rights of the\nXCMStimied o\u00bb rage A W. 1)\nBUSINESS DECLINE IS\nSLOWING UP, IKE SAYS\nI<IWMHMMMMMMI\nreview material with their sponsor before pre\nsenting a panel before the delegates of the\nPhi Delta Kappa Sorority in bottom photo. They\ndiscussed \"educating America's youth for life\nin q, new era.\" Left to right are: E. C. Tate\n(sponsor), Myrtle McPherson, Ernestine Wide\nman, Jean Covington, Gwendolyn Wales, and\nRudine Thomas. Standing are Gilbert Thurman,\nLoretta Fowlkes, and Adolphus Drain.\u2014(World's\nPhoto by Perry)\nTuskegee Prexy\nWill Address The\nHungry Club Today\nDr. Luther H. Foster, President\nof Tuskegee Institute, will speak\nto the Butler Street YMCA Hungry\nClub today at 12:15. He will speak\non the subject, \u201cThe Citizen\u2019s\nSchool: An Appraisal and Evaluat\nion.\u201d Dr. Foster, son of the late\nDr. L. H. Foster, Sr., former Presi\ndent of Virginia State College, dis\ntinguished himself as Business\nManager of Howard University and\nTuskegee Institute before taking\nover the presidency of Tuskegee\nInstitute. He is a strong civic lead\ner who is a member of many im\nportant boards and committees\nwhich deal with material anj in\ntemational problems. Friends and\ngraduates of Tuskegee Institute and\nDr. Foster are particularly invited\nto join the regular Hungry Club\nmembers at this session. All per\nsons are asked to make reservation\nby calling the Butter Street YMCA\nat JiA. MOM.\nFBI Chief Lauds\nVirginia Pastor\nFor Ousting Reds\nWASHINGTON. (ANP) The\nRev. W. B. Westbrook, pastor of\nNew Central Baptist Church, Nor\nfolk, has been commended by FBI\nDirector J. Edgar Hoover, for ex\npelling suspected communists from\na branch meeting of the NAACP,\nin Norfolk in the early 1950\u2019b.\nMr. Hoover disclosed the action\nof the Norfolk pastor in his recent\nly published oook, \u201cMasters of De\nceit.\u201d He cited the explusion of the\nalleged Reds as \u201cone of the most\neffective anti-communist measures\nI have heard of.\u201d\nThe NAACP president was not\ncited by name in Mr. Hoover\u2019s\nbook, but during the period cover\ned in the book Rev. Mr. Westbrook\nwas president of the Norfolk\nNAACP. Before Rev. Mr. Westbrook\nbecame branch president three or\nfour white people suspected of being\ncommunists or communist sympa\nthizers were active in the branch\nand attended branch meetings regu\nlarly, and on som e occasions at\ntended board sessions that proceded\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nLABORS MEANY SAYS\nSITUATION IS WORSE\nBy JAMES LEE\nWASHINGTON (INS) Unemployment in the U. S. was\ndisclosed to have risen by only 25,000 in March, smallest month\nly increase since the recession began last fall. President Eisen\nhowever said the figures indicate the business decline is \"slow\ning up.\" 1\nThe government also reported\nthat total employment in the njk\ntion, reflecting a spring upturn in\nfarm and other outdoor jobs,\nclimbed by 323,000 last month, to\na total of 62,311,000, about 4,900,000\nunder the all-time record high, set\nlast July.\nThe jobless total mounted to 5,-\n198,000, highest since 1941 but the\nsmall monthly rise contrasting\nwith the 679,000 increase in Febru\nary and the 1,100,000 jump in Janu\nary\u2014indicated a leveling off of the\nbusiness slump.\nCutbacks in factory jobs account\ned for most of the unemployment\nincrease. The Commerce and La\nbor Departments, in their joint re\nport, said most of the lost jobs\noccurred in durable goods indus\ntries, particularly automobiles, ma\nchine tools, and metals.\nOne effect of the new figure was\nto strengthen the administration\u2019s\nposition against a quick and mas\nsive tax cut or other drastic anti\nrecession measures.\nMr. Eisenhower made the follow\ning brief comment on the report,\nin a statement issued by White\nHouse News Secretary James C.\nHagerty:\n\u201cThe figures released this morn\ning by the Departments of Com\nmerce and Labor show a pickup\nin jobs in March and a leveling\noff of unemployment. These statis\ntics indicate a slowing up of the\ndecline.\u201d\nAFL CIO President George\nMeany sharply disagreed with Mr.\nEisenhower\u2019s contention that the\neconomic picture shows improve\nment.\nMeany declared in a statement:\n\u201cTh? figures on unemployment and\nemployment in March, released\nTuesday, indicate a continued\ndeepening of the recession.\n'\u201cUnfortunately, there's nothing\nin the government report to indi\ncate that the recession has hit bot\ntom, let alone any sign of a pick\nup.\u201d\nMeany asserted: \u201cThere is no\nthing that we in the AFL CIO\nwould welcome more than an end\nto this recession. But facts are\nfacts and there isn\u2019t a single ray 7\nof sunshine in today\u2019s report.\u201d\nHe noted that unemployment in\ncreased during a period when it\nnormally declines and said: \u201cAs a\nresult, the rate of unemployment\nrose from 6.7 per cent of the labor\nforce in February to seven per\ncent in March, after accounting for\nseasonal factors.\u201d\nThe labor spokesman added that\n\u201cthe only way to change the situ\nation is for the government to act\nnow.\u201d He said: \u201cOptimistic press\nreleases won\u2019t end this recession\nbut legislation can.\u201d\nONLY A RATTLESNAKE\nLITTLE ROCK, Ark.\u2014Mrs. W. C.\nAmond returned home from a visit\nto a neighbor and her 2 1-2 year\nold son, Jimmy, told her he had\nkilled \u201ca thing\u201d with his hoe, ex\nplaining: \u201cIt was moving around,\nlocking at us. We didn\u2019t like the\nway it was acting, so I killed it\nwith my hoe.\u201d\nThe \u201cthing\u201d was a rattlesnake.\nSan Francisco\nHas Negro Judge\nSAN FRANCISCO. (ANP)\nGov. Godwin Knight of California\nrecently appointed Atty. John W\nBussey a judge of the San Fran\ncisco Municipal Court, making him\nthe first Negro ever to win such\nan appointment in the city\u2019s his\ntory.\nBussey succeeds Municipal Judge\nGerald S. Levin who was elevated 1\nto the superior Court bench. Judge\nLevin replaced Judge Alvert C.\nWollenberg, who was nominated for\na federal judgeship.\nLAWYER AND TEACHER\nAt 54, the athletically built Bus\nsey is a veteran lawyer who leaves\nbehind him a splendid record both\nas a practicing attorney arm tutor. 1\nHe has guided \u201chundreds\u201d of\nbudding lawyers towards their goal.\nBussey, who is Georgia-born but\nhas lived and practiced law in the\nbay area for more than 26 years,\nreceived the news of his appoint\nment modestly. \"It was somewhat\nof a surprise to me,\u201d he said, add\ning: \u201cIt will be quite a challenge. I\nIt\u2019s something, I suppose, every\nlawyer and law student thinks of.\nOn e sort of floats in mid-air tor i\nwbuo btiow setuea aowa,\" 1\nCITY\nEDITION\n\u201cNEWS WHILE\nIT IS NEWS\"\nGroup Aids Make\nCity Beautiful\nCampaign Here\nThe Council of Neighbouhood\nOrganizations, an affiliate of the\nAtlanta Urban League, is cooper\nating with the Women\u2019s Chamber\nof Commerce in the \u201cMake Atlan\nta Beautiful Campaign\u201d during the\nmonth of April.\nSeventeen Neighborhood Civic As\nsociations are participating in ths\ndean-up Drive\u2014 Reynolds Town,\nRockdale Park, Cascade Heights,\nHightower Road, Carey Park,\nScottscrossing, Thomasville, Bush\nMountain, Friendly Neighbors, and\nthe Southside Civic League. Parti\ncipating also are the Tenants\u2019 Lea\ngues of Carver, Eagan, Grady,\nPerry, Herndon, and University-\nJoh n Hope Homes. These groups\nhave chosen various projects In\ntrying to \u201cclean-up, paint-up apd\nfix-up\u201d their homes and to en\nhance the appearance of this\nmunity.\nPRIZES PLANNED\nPrizes will be awarded in various\ncategories to participating groups\nby the Chamber of Commerceu T&t\npresident of the Council of\nborhood Organizations t, 0.\nHester of Bland Town. Mrs. Xktb\nryn Brisbane, Oommun\u2019te QMNj^\nzation secretary of tb* JhHm\u00df\nUrban League? is advSor\ngrousp; and Mr. Otelus flMXtada'\nis chairman of the clean-up\nmittee.\nSOUTH ATLANTA\nThe South Atlanta Coordinating\nCouncil\u2019s Clean-up Committee,\nder the chairmanship of R. K\nCureton, wm klek-off its campaign\non Monday April 14, with a parade\nwhich will start at Carver Hotifee\nplay area st 10:00 am. It will pass\nthe reviewing stand at Price High\nSchool. The Council will also award\nprizes for parade posters and essays\non \u201cHow to Make Our Oommun*\nity More Attractive.\u201d The Rev. T.\nP.f Grissom is chairman of the -co\nordinating council.\nNashville Board\nFiles School\nIntegration Plan\nNASHVILLE, Tenn, (INS)\u2014 The\nNashville Board of Education filed\nits plan for gradual desegregation\nof city public schools Monday.\nThe three-point plan calls for\ncompulsory segregation based bn\nrace to be abolished in all second\ngrade schools for the scholartta\nyear beginning September IMS.\nThereafter one additional grade\nwill be desegregated each year.\nIn complying with a Federal\nCourt order, the board's plan ate\nprovides with zoning transfers\nwhich shall \u201ccontinue in force and\neffect with respect to each addi\ntional grade as the plan beoomee\napplicable to such grade.\u201d\nEAGER TO FACE CHALLENGB\nAsked if he anticipated any trou\nble along racial lines during Ids\ntenure on the bench, h e said bg\ndidn\u2019t. \u2018T don\u2019t anticipate any\ntrouble. I have no feehnge along\nthese lines. Generally, I\u2019Ve gotten\nalong with all groups.\u201d\nBussey is not considered an aH>\nout campaigner for Negro lights\nalthough he did serve for .a time\nas a member of the local eIMMMRg\nof the NAACP. That was from I*3\nto 1936 \u201cwhen I had plenty ot tbne\nbecause of the depression,\u201d be sit\nplained. He said the duties invbMr*\ned primarily organizational pfeb\nlems since there weren\u2019t too waciy\nNegro people living here at tba\ntime.\nAs a lawyer, Bussey is wen pre\npared for his new duties. A gObd\nuate of the University of Oaltisrala\nand Harvard university law 9^3001,\nhis career includes four wrr w\ndeputy district attorney of Alamda\nCounty, and two years ss a Jaw\nteacher at Howard University in\nWashington, D. C. He was also a\nleader in several local qMa emo*","height":"25551","width":"20631"}}
